Notes: when doing a=0.9995 with around steps = 40,000 we get M = 5000 and expected was 4000. as a -> 1, with fixed steps = 40,000 we end up with worse and worse M’s sorta proportional to the expected. a= 0.9995: “Suggested M: 5701.000000, expected 3999.000000” a= 0.995: “Suggested M: 532.000000, expected 399.000000” a=0.95: “Suggested M: 51.000000, expected 39.000000” with steps = 40 * t_exp: a=0.25: “Suggested M: 5.000000, expected 1.666667” a=0.5: “Suggested M: 4.000000, expected 3.000000” a=0.75: a=0.9: “Suggested M: 21.000000, expected 19.000000” -> steps = 40 * t_exp actually better than a ton of steps in some cases, due to selection of C?

# Dependencies
library(ggplot2)
library(LaplacesDemon)
source("./generic.R")
source("./deshMethod.R")
states_visited <- c()
acfs <- c()
# Specific to autoregression 
a = 0.95
b = 2
exp_m <- 1 + 2*(a/(1-a))
#steps = 40*exp_m
steps = 10000

get_next_step <- function(prev) {
  w <- rnorm(n=1, mean=0, sd=1)
  next_val <- a * prev + b * w
  return(next_val)
}

get_init_state <- function() {
  init_sd <- b^2 / (1-a^2)
  init_state <- rnorm(n=1, mean=0, sd=init_sd)
  return(init_state)
}

states_visited <- asim(get_init_state(), get_next_step, steps)
exp_sd <- b^2 / (1-a^2)
sprintf("Mean: %f, Variance: %f, expected variance: %f", mean(states_visited), sd(states_visited)^2, exp_sd)
[1] "Mean: -0.060359, Variance: 9.046573, expected variance: 9.142857"
